# 🛡️ Rules of Engagement (ROE)
Penetration Testing Engagement

---

## 📌 Purpose

This document defines how penetration testing activities will be conducted to ensure safety, legality, and minimal disruption.

---

## 🕒 Testing Schedule

- Non-invasive testing: During business hours
- Invasive testing: Between 2:00 AM – 6:00 AM (Friday – Sunday)

---

## 📡 Communication Protocol

- Primary communication: Reports and teleconferences
- Critical vulnerabilities: Immediate notification to client
- Escalation: Contact designated IT/security personnel

---

## 🚫 Prohibited Activities

The following actions are NOT permitted:

- Denial-of-Service (DoS) attacks
- Testing outside defined scope
- Unauthorized data exfiltration
- Accessing third-party systems

---

## ⚙️ Security Controls

The following controls are active during testing:

- Firewalls
- Intrusion Detection Systems (IDS)

Note: Testing must account for active security controls.

---

## 🔐 Sensitive Data Handling

- All sensitive data must be handled securely
- No unnecessary data extraction
- NDA must be signed prior to testing
- Any accidental exposure must be reported immediately

---

## 🌐 Testing Origin

- Testing will originate from:
  - Internal IT Department VLAN

---

## 🧪 Allowed Testing Activities

- Internal network testing
- Vulnerability scanning
- Controlled exploitation (proof-of-concept only)

---

## ⚠️ Incident Handling

If any system instability or disruption occurs:

1. Testing must stop immediately  
2. Client must be notified  
3. Issue must be documented  

---

## 🛑 Kill Switch

Testing must be stopped immediately if:

- Critical systems are impacted
- Data integrity is at risk
- Client requests termination

---

## 👥 Client Contacts

Primary contacts include:

- Warehouse Manager  
- IT Director  
- Operations Manager  

---

## ⚖️ Legal & Ethical Compliance

All testing must:

- Stay within authorized scope  
- Comply with applicable laws  
- Follow ethical hacking standards  

---

## ⚠️ Disclaimer

This ROE is for educational purposes and should be reviewed by a legal professional before real-world use.

---
